  <h2>Step-by-Step: How to Clean a Wood Heater</h2>

  <!-- Step 1 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">1</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Wait until the heater is completely cold</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Allow at least 24 hours after the last fire before cleaning. Ash retains heat much longer than most people expect — even ash that looks cold and grey can contain live embers underneath. Touch the outside of the heater to confirm it's fully cooled.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 2 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">2</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Lay down newspaper and put on your gear</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Spread old newspaper or a drop sheet in front of the heater before opening the door. Put on your gloves and dust mask now — once you start shovelling, fine particles become airborne quickly.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 3 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">3</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Remove ash from the firebox</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Use your ash shovel to transfer ash into the metal bucket. Work from the back forward, and leave a thin layer (1–2cm) on the floor of the firebox — a small bed of ash actually helps insulate and improves combustion for the next fire. Sweep any remaining ash with the small brush.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 4 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">4</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Clean the glass door</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Black or brown buildup on the glass is caused by incomplete combustion — usually from burning wet wood or running the heater too low. To clean it: dampen a sheet of newspaper, dip it lightly into the ash from the firebox, and rub the glass in small circles. The fine ash acts as a mild abrasive. Wipe clean with a damp cloth. For stubborn staining, use a purpose-made fireplace glass cleaner — follow the instructions on the label.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 5 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">5</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Wipe down the firebox interior</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Use a damp cloth to wipe the inside surfaces of the firebox — the sides, back, and top. Remove any loose soot or debris. Don't use soap or chemical cleaners inside the firebox — just water. Check the baffle plate (the horizontal metal plate near the top) for soot buildup and wipe it down if accessible.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 6 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">6</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Check the door seal</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">The rope gasket around the door keeps the heater airtight, which is what allows you to control the burn rate. To test it: close the door on a piece of paper and try to pull it out. If it slides out easily, the seal has worn and needs replacing. A worn door seal affects efficiency significantly — the heater will burn through wood faster and be harder to control.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 7 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">7</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Clean the external surfaces</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Wipe down the outside of the heater with a dry cloth. For cast iron models, a very light coat of stove black or high-temperature paint can refresh the finish if it's looking dull. Check that the air control levers move freely and aren't gummed up with dust or debris.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

