  <h2>The Part You Can't Clean Yourself: The Flue</h2>

  <p>Everything above is what you can safely do yourself. But there's a critical part of the system that DIY cleaning doesn't reach: the flue.</p>

  <p>The flue is the pipe that carries combustion gases from the firebox up through the roof and out. Every time you burn wood, creosote — a dark, sticky byproduct of combustion — deposits on the inside walls of the flue. Over time it builds up. And creosote is highly flammable.</p>

  <div style="background:#fff3cd;border-left:4px solid #c8500a;border-radius:8px;padding:1rem 1.1rem;margin:1.4rem 0;">
    <strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Chimney fires start in the flue, not the firebox.</strong>
    <p style="margin:.4rem 0 0;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.6;">A chimney fire can reach over 1000°C. Many go undetected — a roaring or crackling sound from the flue when no fire is lit is a warning sign. Heavy creosote buildup is the cause. Annual professional cleaning removes it before it becomes a hazard.</p>
  </div>

  <p>A professional flue clean uses specialist brushes that scrub the full length of the flue from above, combined with a vacuum to contain the debris. It takes about 45–60 minutes. You won't be able to replicate this from inside the firebox — the buildup is in the pipe above, not in the firebox itself.</p>

