  <h2>Common Problems You Might Notice While Cleaning</h2>

  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.8rem;margin:1.1rem 0 1.6rem;">

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        🪟 The glass is staining black again very quickly<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">This almost always means the wood is too wet. Wet wood burns at a lower temperature, produces more smoke and incomplete combustion products — which coat the glass. Try sourcing properly seasoned hardwood (12+ months dried). If the problem continues with dry wood, it may mean the heater is being run too low — keep the air controls open higher until the fire is well established.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        🔥 There's a strong smell when the heater is first lit<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Some smell on first light is normal, especially at the start of the season. But a strong burning or acrid smell that persists beyond the first 10–15 minutes usually indicates creosote in the flue burning off or — more seriously — a partial blockage. If the smell is strong and smoky, get the flue checked before using the heater further.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        🐦 There's debris or nesting material in the firebox<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Twigs, leaves, feathers or debris falling into the firebox usually means there's no flue cap (or a damaged one) and birds have been nesting in the flue. Don't use the heater until the flue has been professionally inspected and cleared — a nest inside a flue is a fire hazard and will block the draw. A new stainless flue cap will prevent this from happening again.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        💨 The door is hard to open or won't seal properly<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">If the door is stiff, the hinges may need lubricating with high-temperature grease. If the door won't seal flush, check whether the rope gasket is compressed or worn — run the paper test (close the door on a sheet of paper, if it pulls out easily the seal is gone). A worn gasket lets uncontrolled air in, which makes the heater burn faster and run hotter than it should. Gasket replacement is a repair job for a heater technician.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

  </div>

  <h2>How Often Should You Clean a Wood Heater?</h2>

  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.5rem;margin:1rem 0 1.4rem;">
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">✓</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Remove ash:</strong> Every 2–4 fires, or when the ash builds up more than 5cm. Leaving too much ash restricts airflow.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">✓</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Clean the glass:</strong> Weekly during heavy use, or whenever visibility through the glass becomes poor.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">✓</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Full firebox clean:</strong> At the start and end of each season (typically March/April and October).</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">✓</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Professional flue clean:</strong> Once a year minimum. Twice a year if the heater is used heavily (5+ nights per week through winter).</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">✓</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Door seal check:</strong> Once per season. Replace immediately if it's failing the paper test.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>What to Do With the Ash</h2>

  <p>Wood ash is alkaline and makes an excellent garden addition — particularly for vegetable gardens and fruit trees that prefer a less acidic soil. Scatter it thinly around the base of plants (avoid piling it up, as undiluted ash can burn roots). Don't use ash from fires where treated timber, cardboard or rubbish was burned — only clean hardwood ash is safe for the garden.</p>

  <p>If you're not using it in the garden, bag it in a sealed plastic bag and put it in the general waste bin. Let it sit in the sealed metal bucket for at least 72 hours before transferring — even ash that appears cold can contain live embers.</p>

  <h2>The Honest Summary</h2>

  <p>The DIY part of cleaning a wood heater is straightforward and worth doing regularly: empty the ash, clean the glass, wipe down the firebox, check the door seal. These things take 20–30 minutes and make a genuine difference to how the heater performs.</p>

  <p>The flue is the part you can't do yourself. It's also the part that matters most for fire safety. If the heater hasn't had a professional flue clean in the last 12 months — or you don't know when it was last done — book one before you light the first fire of the season. It's an hour's work and $249. A chimney fire is considerably more expensive.</p>

